ex qua, etc.: the reading of P is: ex qna monet etiam nos procupidinem amoris et dicit in formari et labi. Plato (Sympos. 203 A) gives a elue to the solution of this corrupt passage: οὗτοι δὴ οἱ δαίμονες πολλοί τε καὶ παντοδαποί εἰσιν, εἷς δὲ τούτων ἐστὶ καὶ ὁ ’Ἔρως Cf. 195 E, 196 A. Procupidinem of the MS„ a word found no place else, was prob. a marginal gloss explanatory of an orig. daemonem amoris (pro (“i11stead of ’') cupi- dinem). A careless scribe might have been misled by the similarity between daemonem and the ending of cupidinem to insert the marg. gloss as one word, taking it to be the original form.
